<!-- 03 BRAND-SPECIFIC NOTES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03, Brand-specific service notes</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we see in the field, by brand.</h2>

    <p><strong>Heat &amp; Glo (Hearth &amp; Home Technologies).</strong> Most common premium direct-vent installer in SoCal. Series: SL-550TR, SL-750TR, 8000 Series, Cerona. Common failures: thermopile at 8-10 years, blower at 6-8 years, remote receiver at 10+ years. Parts widely available through licensed distributors. We stock thermopiles, igniters, and common remote receivers on the van.</p>

    <p><strong>Heatilator (also Hearth &amp; Home).</strong> Sister brand to Heat &amp; Glo, similar parts catalog. Heatilator Constitution and Eclipse series most common in SoCal. Same failure patterns as Heat &amp; Glo.</p>

    <p><strong>Majestic (Hearth &amp; Home, same parent).</strong> Direct-vent and vent-free units. Common in Calabasas and Thousand Oaks new construction 2010-2018. Parts interchangeable with Heat &amp; Glo / Heatilator on most components.</p>

    <p><strong>Valor (Canadian, Miles Industries).</strong> Premium European-style direct-vent units. Distinctive log presentations. We see Valor most often in Beverly Hills and Brentwood retrofits. Excellent build quality, failures rare before 10 years. When they happen, parts come through Valor's North American distribution; usually 3-5 days.</p>

    <p><strong>Mendota (Hearth &amp; Home).</strong> Premium direct-vent line. Less common in SoCal than Heat &amp; Glo but appearing more in 2020+ builds. Shares some parts with the Hearth &amp; Home family.</p>

    <p><strong>Lennox Hearth.</strong> Was Lennox-owned, then divested to Innovative Hearth Products. Older Lennox units (2010 and earlier), parts harder to source. Newer IHP-branded units, full parts catalog available. We service both.</p>

    <p><strong>Kingsman.</strong> Canadian, mid-premium. Direct-vent and vent-free. Similar service profile to Heat &amp; Glo.</p>

    <p><strong>Empire / FireGear / outdoor-specific brands.</strong> Outdoor gas fireplaces (sometimes integrated into outdoor kitchens or as standalone fire pits): different sealed combustion architecture. Empire, FireGear, Hearth Products Controls, Real Fyre. Most outdoor installs use a Hearth Products Controls valve or similar. We service all of these.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 DIAGNOSIS PROCESS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04, Diagnosis process</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">When we arrive on a "fireplace doesn't work" call.</h2>

    <ol class="numbered-list">
      <li><strong>Visual safety check.</strong> Flue/vent inspection, glass condition, log placement, gas line condition. 30-second walkthrough.</li>
      <li><strong>Ignition system test.</strong> Does pilot light? Does it stay lit?</li>
      <li><strong>Millivolt test at gas valve.</strong> Measure thermocouple/thermopile output during pilot run. This single test diagnoses the most common failure.</li>
      <li><strong>Remote/wall switch continuity.</strong> Bypass remote at the gas valve to isolate remote vs gas valve.</li>
      <li><strong>Gas pressure check.</strong> At the appliance, confirms supply.</li>
      <li><strong>Blower test (for inserts).</strong> Disconnect thermostat switch, run blower direct.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Most diagnoses take 15-30 minutes. We tell you what's wrong and what it costs before any parts are ordered.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 REAL REPAIR STORIES -->
<section class="section">
